item.title: Masks notably reduce infection risk: study
item.description: Requiring the wearing of masks to prevent the spread of the novel coronavirus in areas at the epicentre of the global pandemic may have prevented tens of thousands of infections, a new study suggests.

item.title: Govt gives cancer treatment projects $12m
item.description: The Morrison government is providing more than $3.5 million to the Cancer Council NSW to research what demand for cancer treatment will look like over the next five years.

item.title: First lady got new deal from Trump: book
item.description: First lady Melania Trump delayed her move to Washington after Donald Trump became president to renegotiate her prenuptial agreement, according to a new book.

item.title: Molotov thrown at Tas police station
item.description: A Molotov cocktail was thrown at a Tasmanian police station overnight but no one was injured in the attack.

item.title: Hunt for killer of Vic man ramps up
item.description: The hunt for the killer of Victorian man Jarrad Lovison has ramped up in the state.

item.title: Two dead, child injured in Vic crash
item.description: Two people have died in a car crash in Victoria with a woman and child also injured.

item.title: Seattle cops told to stop using tear gas
item.description: A US judge has ordered Seattle police to temporarily halt using tear gas, pepper spray and flash-bang devices to break up peaceful protests.

item.title: Regional airports get $41.2m in support
item.description: Sixty regional airports will receive a share of $41.2 million in funding to help Australia's aviation industry get through the COVID-19 pandemic, Deputy Prime Minister Michael McCormack said.

item.title: Beijing market closes over new virus cases
item.description: Authorities in Beijing have temporarily shut a major wholesale agricultural market following a rise in locally transmitted novel coronavirus infections in China's capital city over the past two days.

item.title: Defaced Churchill statue troubles grandson
item.description: Sir Winston Churchill's grandson says he is "deeply upset" after his grandfather's statue was defaced and has been boarded up ahead of more expected anti-racism protests in London.
